<subsection xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"><title> Separable Form </title>

    <p>
        The separation of variables method works when we can separate the dependent and independent variables by multiplication. Let's define this property formally.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="separable">
        <statement>
            A first-order differential equation is <term>separable</term> if it can be written in the <term>separable form</term>:
            <men xml:id="separable-form">\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x) \cdot g(y)</men>
        </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
        The notation <m>f(x)</m> and <m>g(y)</m> are place-holders for expressions that only contain the variable <m>x</m> and the variable <m>y</m>, respectively. Equivalently, the definition could be written as
        <me> \frac{dy}{dx} = \left(
        \begin{array}{c}
            \text{ONLY } x \text{ terms} \\
            \text{ and/or constants}\\
        \end{array} \right) \cdot \left(
        \begin{array}{c}
            \text{ONLY } y \text{ terms} \\
            \text{and/or constants}\\
        \end{array} \right),
        </me>
        but it is much easier to just write <m>f(x) \cdot g(y)</m>.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="separable-examples"><title> Separable Differential Equations </title>

        <p>
            The following first-order differential equations are separable.
            <tabular>
                <row><cell><m/></cell></row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = 6xy</m></cell><cell/>
                    <cell><m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = (x^2 + 1)(y - 6)^3</m></cell><cell/>
                    <cell><m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = \cos(x)\sin(y)</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </p>

    </example>

    <example xml:id="non-separable-examples"><title> Non-Separable Differential Equations </title>

        <p>
            The following first-order differential equations are not separable.
            <tabular>
                <row><cell><m/></cell></row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = 6x + y</m></cell><cell/>
                    <cell><m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = (x + y)(y - 6)^3</m></cell><cell/>
                    <cell><m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = \cos(x - y)</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </p>

    </example>

    <xi:include href="./c2-s2-ss1-interactives.ptx" />

</subsection>
